#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:253
msgid "Separate core math library"
msgstr "獨立的核心數學程式庫"

#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:255
msgid ""
"The core math functions (sin, cos, etc... for basic C types) have been put "
"into a separate library; it acts as a compatibility layer, to support most "
"C99 maths functions (real only for now). The library includes platform-"
"specific fixes for various maths functions, such as using those versions "
"should be more robust than using your platform functions directly. The API "
"for existing functions is exactly the same as the C99 math functions API; "
"the only difference is the npy prefix (npy_cos vs cos)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:263
msgid "The core library will be made available to any extension in 1.4.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:266
msgid "CPU arch detection"
msgstr "CPU 架構偵測"

#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:268
msgid ""
"npy_cpu.h defines numpy specific CPU defines, such as NPY_CPU_X86, etc... "
"Those are portable across OS and toolchains, and set up when the header is "
"parsed, so that they can be safely used even in the case of cross-"
"compilation (the values is not set when numpy is built), or for multi-arch "
"binaries (e.g. fat binaries on Max OS X)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.3.0-notes.rst:274
msgid ""
"npy_endian.h defines numpy specific endianness defines, modeled on the glibc "
"endian.h. NPY_BYTE_ORDER  is equivalent to BYTE_ORDER, and one of "
"NPY_LITTLE_ENDIAN or NPY_BIG_ENDIAN is defined. As for CPU archs, those are "
"set when the header is parsed by the compiler, and as such can be used for "
"cross-compilation and multi-arch binaries."
msgstr ""
